[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1434},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F09\u002F22\u002Freact-08-useeffect\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F09\u002F22\u002Freact-08-useeffect\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F09\u002F22\u002Freact-08-useeffect\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F09\u002F22\u002Freact-08-useeffect\u002F":1411,"related:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F09\u002F22\u002Freact-08-useeffect\u002F":1420},"\u002Freact\u002F20220922\u002F836180798\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1394,"date":1395,"description":1396,"extension":1397,"lang":1398,"meta":1399,"navigation":231,"path":1400,"readingMinutes":1401,"seo":1402,"standalone":1403,"stem":1404,"tags":1405,"tldr":1408,"updated":1395,"url":1409,"__hash__":1410},"content\u002Fen\u002FReact\u002Freact-08-useeffect.md","React Basics: Getting to Know useEffect (and Side Effects) — (8)","1003104251",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1382},"minimark",[11,16,25,29,35,38,41,44,60,63,70,73,123,126,141,152,155,161,167,170,183,192,354,365,376,381,387,493,498,508,517,521,527,610,615,628,632,648,662,790,795,810,813,832,837,843,847,850,862,926,941,1218,1223,1236,1249,1257,1261,1273,1355,1360,1364,1367,1378],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19,20,24],"p",{},"Next up we're getting to know a new React Hook: ",[21,22,23],"code",{},"useEffect",". The name looks a little odd at first glance, because if you translate it straight into plain English it's basically \"use effect.\" Effect of what, exactly? Let's find out.",[12,26,28],{"id":27},"side-effect","Side Effect",[17,30,31,32,34],{},"Before we touch ",[21,33,23],{},", there's one concept we need to nail down first: the Side Effect. So what's a Side Effect?",[17,36,37],{},"The classic analogy is the \"medicine\" a doctor prescribes.",[17,39,40],{},"Yep, exactly the kind you're thinking of — the stuff on the prescription. Picture it: after you catch a cold, the bag of meds you get usually has \"side effects\" printed on it somewhere, and those side effects might be things like an allergic reaction, drowsiness, or an upset stomach.",[17,42,43],{},"I'll admit the word \"side effect\" makes everything sound bad, but a side effect can actually be helpful and beneficial too. Here's a quick way to look at it:",[45,46,51],"pre",{"className":47,"code":48,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"language-txt shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","After you take the medicine your body gets better, but along with it comes an upset stomach\n","txt","",[21,52,53],{"__ignoreMap":50},[54,55,58],"span",{"class":56,"line":57},"line",1,[54,59,48],{},[17,61,62],{},"That little description actually contains two side effects: \"your body gets better\" and \"an upset stomach.\" So side effects aren't all bad.",[17,64,65,66,69],{},"So why am I bringing this up? Well, the things we run into all the time — AJAX, DOM manipulation, even ",[21,67,68],{},"console.log"," — are all a kind of side effect. And in real development we lean on side effects constantly, so understanding them helps you avoid writing some dangerous code.",[17,71,72],{},"So in the world of code, what does a side effect look like? For example, reassigning a value is also a side effect:",[45,74,78],{"className":75,"code":76,"language":77,"meta":50,"style":50},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var myName = 'Ray';\n... \u002F\u002F a few thousand lines later\nmyName = 'Array';\n","js",[21,79,80,100,110],{"__ignoreMap":50},[54,81,82,86,90,93,97],{"class":56,"line":57},[54,83,85],{"class":84},"sWyjQ","var",[54,87,89],{"class":88},"sMAXC"," myName ",[54,91,92],{"class":84},"=",[54,94,96],{"class":95},"sTRMh"," 'Ray'",[54,98,99],{"class":88},";\n",[54,101,103,106],{"class":56,"line":102},2,[54,104,105],{"class":84},"...",[54,107,109],{"class":108},"sQrFR"," \u002F\u002F a few thousand lines later\n",[54,111,113,116,118,121],{"class":56,"line":112},3,[54,114,115],{"class":88},"myName ",[54,117,92],{"class":84},[54,119,120],{"class":95}," 'Array'",[54,122,99],{"class":88},[17,124,125],{},"Bet you didn't expect that reassigning a value counts as a side effect.",[17,127,128,129,132,133,136,137,140],{},"But it's true — anytime you mutate the original value, that's a side effect. You can see the original value above is ",[21,130,131],{},"'Ray'",", and then who-knows-how-many hundreds or thousands of lines later we reassign ",[21,134,135],{},"myName"," to ",[21,138,139],{},"'Array'",". That whole process can lead to unpredictable bugs that are a pain to track down.",[17,142,143,144,151],{},"This is just a rough overview, of course. If this area interests you, check out something I wrote earlier — \"",[145,146,150],"a",{"href":147,"rel":148},"https:\u002F\u002Fisraynotarray.com\u002Fother\u002F20211219\u002F3830068067\u002F",[149],"nofollow","A Fun, Simple Take on Functional Programming in JavaScript","\" (article in Mandarin) — for more detail.",[17,153,154],{},"I'm only touching on what a side effect is here, since the React docs put it like this:",[156,157,158],"blockquote",{},[17,159,160],{},"Data fetching, setting up a subscription, and manually changing the DOM in React components are all examples of side effects.",[17,162,163,164,166],{},"Alright, now that we've got a rough idea of what a side effect is, let's get to know ",[21,165,23],{},".",[12,168,23],{"id":169},"useeffect",[17,171,172,174,175,179,180,182],{},[21,173,23],{}," is mostly used when we want to do something ",[176,177,178],"em",{},"after"," the screen renders. Basically you're telling React, \"hey, after you render, remember to run this stuff for me.\" The things you put in here are usually side-effect-related, so as a rule of thumb, any behavior that produces a side effect is best placed inside ",[21,181,23],{}," — things like the AJAX calls and DOM changes I mentioned earlier.",[17,184,185,186,188,189,166],{},"And if you came from Vue, what's ",[21,187,23],{}," similar to? It's kind of like the Composition API's ",[21,190,191],{},"onMounted",[45,193,195],{"className":75,"code":194,"language":77,"meta":50,"style":50},"const { createApp, ref, onMounted } = Vue;\n\nconst app = createApp({\n  setup() {\n    const text = ref('Hello Ray.');\n    \n    onMounted(() => {\n      console.log(text.value)\n    })\n  }\n});\n\napp.mount('#app');\n",[21,196,197,227,233,250,259,282,288,303,315,321,327,333,338],{"__ignoreMap":50},[54,198,199,202,205,209,212,215,217,219,222,224],{"class":56,"line":57},[54,200,201],{"class":84},"const",[54,203,204],{"class":88}," { ",[54,206,208],{"class":207},"sCcAr","createApp",[54,210,211],{"class":88},", ",[54,213,214],{"class":207},"ref",[54,216,211],{"class":88},[54,218,191],{"class":207},[54,220,221],{"class":88}," } ",[54,223,92],{"class":84},[54,225,226],{"class":88}," Vue;\n",[54,228,229],{"class":56,"line":102},[54,230,232],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":231},true,"\n",[54,234,235,237,240,243,247],{"class":56,"line":112},[54,236,201],{"class":84},[54,238,239],{"class":207}," app",[54,241,242],{"class":84}," =",[54,244,246],{"class":245},"sj_SG"," createApp",[54,248,249],{"class":88},"({\n",[54,251,253,256],{"class":56,"line":252},4,[54,254,255],{"class":245},"  setup",[54,257,258],{"class":88},"() {\n",[54,260,262,265,268,270,273,276,279],{"class":56,"line":261},5,[54,263,264],{"class":84},"    const",[54,266,267],{"class":207}," text",[54,269,242],{"class":84},[54,271,272],{"class":245}," ref",[54,274,275],{"class":88},"(",[54,277,278],{"class":95},"'Hello Ray.'",[54,280,281],{"class":88},");\n",[54,283,285],{"class":56,"line":284},6,[54,286,287],{"class":88},"    \n",[54,289,291,294,297,300],{"class":56,"line":290},7,[54,292,293],{"class":245},"    onMounted",[54,295,296],{"class":88},"(() ",[54,298,299],{"class":84},"=>",[54,301,302],{"class":88}," {\n",[54,304,306,309,312],{"class":56,"line":305},8,[54,307,308],{"class":88},"      console.",[54,310,311],{"class":245},"log",[54,313,314],{"class":88},"(text.value)\n",[54,316,318],{"class":56,"line":317},9,[54,319,320],{"class":88},"    })\n",[54,322,324],{"class":56,"line":323},10,[54,325,326],{"class":88},"  }\n",[54,328,330],{"class":56,"line":329},11,[54,331,332],{"class":88},"});\n",[54,334,336],{"class":56,"line":335},12,[54,337,232],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":231},[54,339,341,344,347,349,352],{"class":56,"line":340},13,[54,342,343],{"class":88},"app.",[54,345,346],{"class":245},"mount",[54,348,275],{"class":88},[54,350,351],{"class":95},"'#app'",[54,353,281],{"class":88},[355,356,364],"iframe",{"height":357,"style":358,"scrolling":359,"title":360,"src":361,"frameBorder":359,"loading":362,"allowTransparency":363,"allowFullScreen":363},300,"width: 100%;","no","(63)Vue v-model","https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fembed\u002FyLKmjQp?default-tab=html%2Cresult","lazy","true","\n  See the Pen \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fpen\u002FyLKmjQp\">\n  (63)Vue v-model\u003C\u002Fa> by Ray (\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\">@hsiangfeng\u003C\u002Fa>)\n  on \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\">CodePen\u003C\u002Fa>.\n",[17,366,367,368,370,371,373,374,166],{},"So I said ",[21,369,23],{}," is \"remember to run this stuff after rendering,\" but ",[21,372,23],{}," actually takes two arguments: a function and an array. The second one, the array, is optional, so depending on how you use it you'll get different results. Let's walk through the various ways to use ",[21,375,23],{},[377,378,380],"h3",{"id":379},"after-every-render","After Every Render",[17,382,383,384,386],{},"First let's look at the first ",[21,385,23],{}," example:",[45,388,392],{"className":389,"code":390,"language":391,"meta":50,"style":50},"language-jsx shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","function App (){\n  const [count, setCount] = React.useState(0);\n\n  React.useEffect(() => {\n    console.log('render');\n  })\n  \n  return (\n    \u003Cdiv>\n      \u003Cbutton type=\"button\" onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>\n        Count is: { count }\n      \u003C\u002Fbutton>\n    \u003C\u002Fdiv>\n  )\n}\n\nconst app = document.querySelector('#app');\nconst root = ReactDOM.createRoot(app);\nroot.render(\u003CApp \u002F>);\n","jsx",[21,393,394,399,404,408,413,418,423,428,433,438,443,448,453,458,464,470,475,481,487],{"__ignoreMap":50},[54,395,396],{"class":56,"line":57},[54,397,398],{},"function App (){\n",[54,400,401],{"class":56,"line":102},[54,402,403],{},"  const [count, setCount] = React.useState(0);\n",[54,405,406],{"class":56,"line":112},[54,407,232],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":231},[54,409,410],{"class":56,"line":252},[54,411,412],{},"  React.useEffect(() => {\n",[54,414,415],{"class":56,"line":261},[54,416,417],{},"    console.log('render');\n",[54,419,420],{"class":56,"line":284},[54,421,422],{},"  })\n",[54,424,425],{"class":56,"line":290},[54,426,427],{},"  \n",[54,429,430],{"class":56,"line":305},[54,431,432],{},"  return (\n",[54,434,435],{"class":56,"line":317},[54,436,437],{},"    \u003Cdiv>\n",[54,439,440],{"class":56,"line":323},[54,441,442],{},"      \u003Cbutton type=\"button\" onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>\n",[54,444,445],{"class":56,"line":329},[54,446,447],{},"        Count is: { count }\n",[54,449,450],{"class":56,"line":335},[54,451,452],{},"      \u003C\u002Fbutton>\n",[54,454,455],{"class":56,"line":340},[54,456,457],{},"    \u003C\u002Fdiv>\n",[54,459,461],{"class":56,"line":460},14,[54,462,463],{},"  )\n",[54,465,467],{"class":56,"line":466},15,[54,468,469],{},"}\n",[54,471,473],{"class":56,"line":472},16,[54,474,232],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":231},[54,476,478],{"class":56,"line":477},17,[54,479,480],{},"const app = document.querySelector('#app');\n",[54,482,484],{"class":56,"line":483},18,[54,485,486],{},"const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(app);\n",[54,488,490],{"class":56,"line":489},19,[54,491,492],{},"root.render(\u003CApp \u002F>);\n",[355,494,497],{"height":357,"style":358,"scrolling":359,"title":495,"src":496,"frameBorder":359,"loading":362,"allowTransparency":363,"allowFullScreen":363},"(69) React  useState","https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fembed\u002FjOzgKmK?default-tab=html%2Cresult","\n  See the Pen \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fpen\u002FjOzgKmK\">\n  (69) React  useState\u003C\u002Fa> by Ray (\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\">@hsiangfeng\u003C\u002Fa>)\n  on \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\">CodePen\u003C\u002Fa>.\n",[17,499,500,501,503,504,507],{},"If you only pass ",[21,502,23],{}," a function and skip the second argument, then once you start clicking the button on screen you'll notice ",[21,505,506],{},"console.log('render')"," keeps firing over and over.",[17,509,510,511,513,514,516],{},"So this first form of ",[21,512,23],{}," means: every time the screen triggers a re-render, ",[21,515,23],{}," runs again right along with it.",[377,518,520],{"id":519},"once","Once",[17,522,523,524,526],{},"But in practice we often only need to run something once, not every single time the screen re-renders. So what do we do? Just pass ",[21,525,23],{}," a second argument — an empty array — and you'll get the run-once behavior:",[45,528,530],{"className":389,"code":529,"language":391,"meta":50,"style":50},"function App (){\n  const [count, setCount] = React.useState(0);\n\n  React.useEffect(() => {\n    console.log('once render');\n  }, []);\n  \n  return (\n    \u003Cdiv>\n      \u003Cbutton type=\"button\" onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>\n        Count is: { count }\n      \u003C\u002Fbutton>\n    \u003C\u002Fdiv>\n  )\n}\n\nconst app = document.querySelector('#app');\nconst root = ReactDOM.createRoot(app);\nroot.render(\u003CApp \u002F>);\n",[21,531,532,536,540,544,548,553,558,562,566,570,574,578,582,586,590,594,598,602,606],{"__ignoreMap":50},[54,533,534],{"class":56,"line":57},[54,535,398],{},[54,537,538],{"class":56,"line":102},[54,539,403],{},[54,541,542],{"class":56,"line":112},[54,543,232],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":231},[54,545,546],{"class":56,"line":252},[54,547,412],{},[54,549,550],{"class":56,"line":261},[54,551,552],{},"    console.log('once render');\n",[54,554,555],{"class":56,"line":284},[54,556,557],{},"  }, []);\n",[54,559,560],{"class":56,"line":290},[54,561,427],{},[54,563,564],{"class":56,"line":305},[54,565,432],{},[54,567,568],{"class":56,"line":317},[54,569,437],{},[54,571,572],{"class":56,"line":323},[54,573,442],{},[54,575,576],{"class":56,"line":329},[54,577,447],{},[54,579,580],{"class":56,"line":335},[54,581,452],{},[54,583,584],{"class":56,"line":340},[54,585,457],{},[54,587,588],{"class":56,"line":460},[54,589,463],{},[54,591,592],{"class":56,"line":466},[54,593,469],{},[54,595,596],{"class":56,"line":472},[54,597,232],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":231},[54,599,600],{"class":56,"line":477},[54,601,480],{},[54,603,604],{"class":56,"line":483},[54,605,486],{},[54,607,608],{"class":56,"line":489},[54,609,492],{},[355,611,614],{"height":357,"style":358,"scrolling":359,"title":612,"src":613,"frameBorder":359,"loading":362,"allowTransparency":363,"allowFullScreen":363},"(70) React  useEffect - After Ever Render","https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fembed\u002FLYdwrMR?default-tab=html%2Cresult","\n  See the Pen \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fpen\u002FLYdwrMR\">\n  (70) React  useEffect - After Ever Render\u003C\u002Fa> by Ray (\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\">@hsiangfeng\u003C\u002Fa>)\n  on \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\">CodePen\u003C\u002Fa>.\n",[17,616,617,618,621,622,624,625,627],{},"Now no matter how much you click the ",[21,619,620],{},"Count"," button, it won't keep re-firing ",[21,623,23],{}," like the previous example did. The concept here is pretty close to Vue's ",[21,626,191],{}," lifecycle.",[377,629,631],{"id":630},"on-state-watching-a-specific-value","On State (watching a specific value)",[17,633,634,635,637,638,641,642,644,645,647],{},"Besides an empty array, the second argument of ",[21,636,23],{}," can also take the thing you want to watch. Watch what, exactly? You watch a ",[21,639,640],{},"useState"," value — whenever that ",[21,643,640],{}," changes, ",[21,646,23],{}," fires.",[17,649,650,651,653,654,657,658,661],{},"One thing to note here, though: ",[21,652,23],{}," always runs once first, so seeing one ",[21,655,656],{},"render"," in the ",[21,659,660],{},"console"," is normal. After that, it only fires again when the value you're watching actually changes.",[45,663,665],{"className":389,"code":664,"language":391,"meta":50,"style":50},"function App (){\n  const [count, setCount] = React.useState(0);\n  const [myName, setMyName] = React.useState('Ray');\n  function sayHi () {\n    window.alert('Hello Ray.');\n  }\n  \n  React.useEffect(() => {\n    console.log('render');\n  }, [ count ])\n  \n  return (\n    \u003Cdiv>\n      \u003Cbutton type=\"button\" onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>\n        Count is: { count }\n      \u003C\u002Fbutton>\n      \u003Chr \u002F>\n      \u003Cbutton type=\"button\" onClick={() => setMyName('QQ')}>\n        Change name { myName }\n      \u003C\u002Fbutton>\n    \u003C\u002Fdiv>\n  )\n}\n\nconst app = document.querySelector('#app');\nconst root = ReactDOM.createRoot(app);\nroot.render(\u003CApp \u002F>);\n",[21,666,667,671,675,680,685,690,694,698,702,706,711,715,719,723,727,731,735,740,745,750,755,760,765,770,775,780,785],{"__ignoreMap":50},[54,668,669],{"class":56,"line":57},[54,670,398],{},[54,672,673],{"class":56,"line":102},[54,674,403],{},[54,676,677],{"class":56,"line":112},[54,678,679],{},"  const [myName, setMyName] = React.useState('Ray');\n",[54,681,682],{"class":56,"line":252},[54,683,684],{},"  function sayHi () {\n",[54,686,687],{"class":56,"line":261},[54,688,689],{},"    window.alert('Hello Ray.');\n",[54,691,692],{"class":56,"line":284},[54,693,326],{},[54,695,696],{"class":56,"line":290}